Understanding Ports and Services & IP types

Port Number: Ensure that the payload of a packet is received to the application/service that its specifically for and is processed by the receiving end of a transmission

Port Info
 - 16-bit unsigned number (ranges from 0-65535)
 - Port number and service name are used to differentiate between services that run on protocols
 - Identifies to a network the specific service, protocol or application that is to receive and process an incoming message. 

List of Protocols
 - TCP (Transmission Control Protocol, transport layer protocols)
 - UDP (User Datagram Protocol (UDP) 
 - DCCP (Datagram Congestion Control Protocol)
 - Stream Control Transmission Control

Port numbers are divided into three groups
 - Well known, Registered, & Dynamic Port Numbers

WellKnown (AKA system Port): numbered 0 to 1023. Numbers are assigned to legacy protocols and services and proprietary protocols. ex: HTTP, SQL, DNS

Registered: numbered to 1024 - 49151. Reserved to specific protocols and applications. 

Dynamic Port (AKA Ephemeral): numbered to 4912-65535. Not permanently assigned to any services and are commonly used as source port numbers for outgoing connections. can be used by virtually for any protocol or service 

Socket (occurs in transport ): Port numbers are appended to logical address (IP address) of incoming messages for destination address. 

